This article discusses President Obama's efforts to stabilize the housing market and protect the middle class. It highlights the progress made in the housing market, such as rising home values and decreased foreclosures, but acknowledges that more work needs to be done. The article outlines the President's ideas to help responsible homeowners refinance, cut red tape to increase access to mortgages, fix the immigration system to increase home values, help rebuild communities hit hardest by foreclosure, and ensure affordable rental housing options. It also emphasizes the need for a more durable and fair housing finance system, with a bigger role for the private sector and an end to bailouts for risky behavior. The article concludes by discussing the President's efforts to simplify the mortgage process, increase incentives for lenders to deliver high-quality loans, and confirm Mel Watt as the FHFA Director to accelerate housing finance reform.